9/15/20, 04:35 - Meghana Kulkarni Arka Book Club: Book Name: The Boy in the Striped Pyjamas
Author: John Boyne
Genre: Historical Fiction
Rating: 🌟🌟🌟🌟🌟

I had read The Nightingale a few months back, and it nearly broke my heart. But, it also made me want to read more about the horrors that people had gone through during the World Wars that happened. At @lindarebello24 's recommendation, I picked up this book, and ended up with a pit in my tummy same as the last time.

The story is told through the eyes of an 8 year old boy, Bruno. His father is a senior commanding officer in the German army, who gets to be in charge of a concentration camp in Poland, and takes his family with him. Bruno is old enough to realise that his life has changed drastically, but not old enough to understand the significance of these changes. He does not understand why they’re now living in such a God-forsaken place, why there are no other houses nearby, and why doesn’t he have kids to play around with. He also doesn’t understand why so many people are living together in the area next to theirs, why they all wear the same striped clothes, and why he’s not allowed to cross over to their house to play with them.

There is nothing worse than watching the cruelty of a war unwind through a child’s mind. The turmoil that goes within the kid wrenches the heck out of your gut. Bruno does not understand racism, or antisemitism, but he understands kindness and hunger and sadness. He behaves in a way any kid would when met with these traits. He repays in kind.

Some say the book is not historically correct. There were no kids in concentration camps. The scenes described in the book couldn’t have happened. This could be correct, I’m not an expert in history. However, it still doesn’t downplay the horror story of the genocide that had taken place during WWII. Read the book for the emotions described, and not for fact checking.

