*1. For your first question:*
I too faced this problem many times when I was building multiple habits, what worked for me was habit stacking and prioritisation:

Once we make something a habit our subconscious is already aware, even with a long break just a few iterations we can get back to it. (If built on a strong purpose)

Once you've built it, it usually takes quite less time to perform. 

As you want to build new habits - you can follow some beautiful rules in the book "Atomic Habits" tells about habit stacking and many more 

Once you develop a new habit, now how do you have the old one with this ?

variations: for example in the morning read books, evening news paper or let's say the new habit is reading books then 1st 5 days in a week read books, sat Sunday - reading the whole weeks news paper to catchup, something like that.

Few factors to consider for building habits:

1. There should be a strong WHY (Purpose) if this exists the habit becomes more fun and impactful. Otherwise it just exists but barely come to use.

2. Very important and crucial aspect is TIME: we all have so many on the To-Do list, but make a "When To-Do" list - by prioritising which is important to you. Plan you habits by allocating time to it and have a bird's eye view.

*To your 2nd Question:*

I too tried doing this 25 things 2 years back, personally I was not effective in achieving atleast 50% of it.

What worked out for me was: 
1. List out the 25 things I want to do for this year.
2. Prioritise top 10 things I wanna do out of 25.
3. Choose only top 5 and do nothing other than that 5. 

This is also called as Warren buffets 5/25 rule. This personally has helped do atleast 80% of all 5 things i wanted to do.

Hope this helps, these are only my experiences. But I guess there are many experienced people in this group who might have different view on this. Feel free to add <This message was edited>
